          "id": "human-resource-management-301-l01-c3",
          "title": "Pay-for-Performance Models",
          "content": "Pay-for-performance is a compensation model that connects how much employees earn to specific outcomes that can be measured. This means that when employees achieve certain goals or perform well, they can receive additional rewards. There are different types of incentives that can motivate individuals. For example, merit pay increases are permanent raises that employees receive based on their performance reviews. This means if an employee does a great job, they might see a boost in their regular paycheck. Bonuses are another form of reward; these are one-time payments given to employees for reaching specific targets or goals. Commissions are also common, especially in sales, where employees earn a percentage of the sales revenue they generate.\nIn addition to individual incentives, there are group incentives that encourage teamwork. Team bonuses reward all members of a team for achieving collective goals, while gainsharing allows employees to share in the benefits of improved productivity as a group. On a larger scale, organizations may offer profit sharing, where employees receive a portion of the company's profits, or stock options, which give employees the right to buy company shares at a set price.\nResearch shows that when goals are clear, measurements are fair, and payouts are meaningful, pay-for-performance can increase productivity by 15-20%. However, it’s important to be aware of potential risks. For instance, this model might encourage employees to focus only on short-term goals, which can lead to neglecting important tasks that are not measured. Therefore, while pay-for-performance can be effective, it’s crucial to implement it thoughtfully to ensure it benefits both employees and the organization as a whole.\nContext recap: Pay-for-performance is a compensation model that connects how much employees earn to specific outcomes that can be measured. This means that when employees achieve certain goals or perform well, they can receive additional rewards. There are different types of incentives that can motivate individuals. For example, merit pay increases are permanent raises that employees receive based on their performance reviews.\nWhy this matters: Pay-for-Performance Models helps learners in Business connect ideas from Compensation, Benefits & Employee Relations to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
